    <button x="195" y="55" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="false" kind="Observer" width="75" display="GO-ONCE">go</button>
    <button x="122" y="55" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="true" kind="Observer" width="56" display="GO">go</button>
    <button x="50" y="55" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="false" kind="Observer" width="55" display="SETUP">setup</button>
    <slider x="40" step="0.01" y="120" max="2.0" width="250" display="v1" height="50" min="0.5" direction="Horizontal" default="1.0" variable="v1"></slider>
    <slider x="40" step="0.01" y="182" max="1.0" width="250" display="v2" height="50" min="0.25" direction="Horizontal" default="0.5" variable="v2"></slider>
    <slider x="40" step="1" y="244" max="800" width="250" display="num-agents" height="50" min="200" direction="Horizontal" default="400.0" variable="num-agents"></slider>
    <input x="40" multiline="false" y="306" height="60" variable="max-ticks" type="number" width="250">5000.0</input>
    <chooser x="40" y="378" height="60" variable="condition" current="0" width="250" display="condition">
      <choice type="string" value="A"></choice>
      <choice type="string" value="B"></choice>
      <choice type="string" value="C"></choice>
    </chooser>
    <slider x="40" step="0.1" y="450" max="10" width="250" display="deposit-amount" height="50" min="2.0" direction="Horizontal" default="5.0" variable="deposit-amount"></slider>
    <slider x="40" step="0.01" y="512" max="0.5" width="250" display="diffusion-rate" height="50" min="0.1" direction="Horizontal" default="0.3" variable="diffusion-rate"></slider>
    <slider x="40" step="0.01" y="574" max="0.1" width="250" display="decay-rate" height="50" min="0.01" direction="Horizontal" default="0.05" variable="decay-rate"></slider>
    <slider x="40" step="0.1" y="629" max="95" width="250" display="chemo-threshold" height="50" min="60" direction="Horizontal" default="70.0" variable="chemo-threshold"></slider>
  </widgets>
  <info><![CDATA[## WHAT IS IT?

Physarum polycephalum — Snell's Law Refraction Simulation
Version: 1.0
Date: 2026-05-02
Source: eurAIka Science Council synthesis (Rounds 1–2)
Target: NetLogo 7.0.4 (latest)

Scientific Hypothesis

Physarum polycephalum explores space via a chemoattractant-trail mechanism and prunes suboptimal paths through flux-driven reinforcement. When the environment is partitioned into two zones with different expansion speeds (warm/damp lower half, cool/dry upper half), the pruned dominant path will cross the media boundary at an x-coordinate predicted by Snell's Law:

sin(θ₁) / sin(θ₂) = v₁ / v₂

where v₁ is the agent speed in the warm/damp zone and v₂ is the agent speed in the cool/dry zone. The primary output is the distribution of x_cross across stochastic replicates.

A secondary mechanistic test: if refraction is Huygens-driven (local first-passage), x_cross stabilizes the moment the front first reaches the food source. If refraction is flux-driven (global optimization), x_cross drifts during the pruning phase. The time course of x_cross distinguishes these hypotheses.

## HOW IT WORKS

The Organism

Physarum polycephalum is a plasmodial slime mold — a single-celled organism that can grow to cover many square centimeters. It explores its environment by extending a fan-shaped sheet of cytoplasm from its leading edge, then withdraws from unproductive regions while reinforcing connections to food sources. The result is an efficient transport network that emerges without any central controller.

Exploration is driven by two coupled biological processes. First, the ectoplasm (outer gel layer) contracts rhythmically via actomyosin motors, driving the inner sol cytoplasm forward and backward in oscillating pulses. Phase gradients across the organism create a net pressure bias toward the growth front, pumping mass outward. Second, the leading edge extends a flat pseudopodial fan where conditions are favorable and retracts it where they are not. New branches form continuously wherever one part of the fan advances faster than its neighbors — there is no discrete branching event.

Once a branch is established, it persists as long as the flux behind it maintains cytoplasmic pressure at its tip. Branches that receive little flux thin and retract; well-fed branches thicken. Extension and pruning are the same mechanism operating at different flux levels.

The Agent Model

This simulation follows the virtual Physarum agent model of Jones (2010). Discrete turtle agents represent units of the exploratory cytoplasmic sol. Each turtle moves forward on each tick, senses a chemoattractant field ahead using three forward-facing sensors (left, center, right at ±45°, distance 9 patches), and turns toward the strongest signal before moving.

After moving, each turtle deposits a fixed quantity of chemoattractant on its current patch. The chemoattractant field is maintained by two global patch processes: diffusion (spreading concentration to neighboring patches each tick) and decay (a fixed fractional loss per tick). Together these processes cause well-traveled paths to sustain high chemo concentrations while neglected paths fade. Agents preferentially follow existing trails, which reinforces them further — this positive feedback loop is what produces path consolidation and eventual pruning of suboptimal routes.

Environmental Zones and Refraction

The world is divided into two horizontal zones at the boundary y = 0. The lower half (Zone 1, warm and damp) supports faster agent movement. The upper half (Zone 2, cool and dry) supports slower movement. Agent movement speed is a patch-level property: each turtle reads the medium-speed value of its current patch and uses that as its step size for that tick. 

All other parameters — chemo deposit amount, diffusion rate, decay rate, sensor geometry — are identical across zones. The slime mold spores are initialized in the lower-left region of Zone 1. The food source is in the upper-right region of Zone 2. Any path between them must cross the zone boundary. Because agents in Zone 1 advance faster, the exploratory front crosses the boundary at an angle. 

The part of the front that enters Zone 2 slows, while the trailing part in Zone 1 continues at full speed. This differential velocity rotates the wavefront — exactly the mechanism described by Huygens' construction in optics — and predicts a boundary crossing point governed by Snell's Law.

During the subsequent pruning phase, the path that first connected the source to the food receives the greatest reinforcement. Competing paths with lower chemo concentrations fade through decay. Over time a single dominant tube emerges. The x-coordinate of the point where this tube crosses the zone boundary (x_cross) is the primary experimental output.

The Mechanistic Test

The time course of x_cross after first contact with the food reveals the mechanism behind the refraction:

If x_cross is stable from the moment of first contact, refraction is a consequence of Huygens wavefront geometry during exploration (the first-arrival path locked in the crossing angle).

If x_cross drifts for hundreds of ticks after first contact before stabilizing, refraction emerges from global flux-optimization during pruning (the network minimizing energy dissipation, shifting the dominant tube toward least resistance).

Both mechanisms are physically plausible. Both predict Snell's Law for the final crossing angle. Only the time course distinguishes them.

## HOW TO USE IT

Setup

SETUP — Initializes the world, assigns zone speeds to patches, marks the source and food locations, and spawns agents at the source. Always click SETUP before starting a new run or changing parameters.

GO — Runs the simulation continuously until either the maximum tick limit is reached or the network has stabilized (determined by the post-contact stabilization period). Click GO again to pause.

GO-ONCE — Advances the simulation by a single tick. Useful for inspecting model behavior step by step during development.

Sliders and Parameters

V1 — Agent movement speed in Zone 1 (warm/damp, lower half).
Units: patch-lengths per tick. Working value: 1.0.
Range: 0.5–2.0.

V2 — Agent movement speed in Zone 2 (cool/dry, upper half).
Units: patch-lengths per tick. Working value: 0.5.
Range: 0.25–1.0.

The ratio V1/V2 is the analog of the optical refractive index ratio. Snell's Law predicts x_cross increases as this ratio increases.

NUM-AGENTS — Number of turtle agents spawned at initialization.
Working value: 400. Range: 200–800.
More agents produce smoother trails and more reproducible paths but increase computation time.

DEPOSIT-AMOUNT — Chemoattractant deposited by each turtle per tick.
Working value: 5.0. Range: 2–10.
Higher values reinforce trails more strongly, speeding up pruning but reducing the diversity of paths explored.

DIFFUSION-RATE — Fraction of each patch's chemo spread to its 8 Moore neighbors per tick. Working value: 0.3. Range: 0.1–0.5.
Higher diffusion widens trails, increasing path diversity but reducing spatial precision of the final tube centerline.

DECAY-RATE — Fractional chemo loss per patch per tick.
Working value: 0.05. Range: 0.01–0.1.
Higher decay accelerates pruning of low-flux paths but may prematurely eliminate valid routes before consolidation is complete.

CHEMO-THRESHOLD — Percentile cutoff (of visited patches by chemo value) used to identify the dominant tube network at measurement time.
Working value: 90. Range: 80–95.
Used in the x_cross measurement procedure.

MAX-TICKS — Hard stop for any run. Working value: 5000.
Adjust upward if networks are not stabilizing before the limit.

CONDITION — Selects the experimental condition:
A: Standard (Zone 1 fast, Zone 2 slow — hypothesis test)
B: Swapped (Zone 1 slow, Zone 2 fast — symmetry test)
C: Homogeneous (both zones equal speed — null model)

Monitors and Plots

x-cross — Current x-coordinate of the dominant tube crossing at the zone boundary. Updated every tick after first contact with food. At run end, this value is the primary experimental measurement.

first-contact-tick — The tick at which any turtle first reached the food patch. Displayed after contact is established.

x-cross-history plot — Time course of x_cross from first contact to run end. A flat line from the start indicates Huygens mechanism; a curve that drifts then stabilizes indicates flux-optimization.

chemo field — Background patch color shows chemoattractant concentration. Brighter patches carry higher concentrations. Watch for the dominant tube to emerge and narrow over time.

Running Experiments

For a single exploratory run: set parameters, click SETUP, click GO, observe the chemo field and x-cross monitor. The dominant tube should be visible within 1000–2000 ticks for standard parameters.

For a batch experiment (50 replicates per condition): use NetLogo's BehaviorSpace tool (Tools menu → BehaviorSpace). Create an experiment that varies RANDOM-SEED across 50 values for each of Conditions A, B, and C. Output variables: x-cross-final, first-contact-tick, total-ticks.

Export results to CSV for analysis in Julia or Python.

## THINGS TO NOTICE

The exploratory fan. In the first 100–300 ticks, watch the agents spread outward from the source in a roughly circular fan. Notice that the fan advances faster in the lower (Zone 1) half than the upper (Zone 2) half. This differential advance is the Huygens mechanism producing the initial path angle before any pruning has occurred. 

The boundary crossing. When the front first reaches y = 0, observe which x-coordinate the leading agents cross at. Compare this to the x_cross monitor. If the Huygens interpretation is correct, this early crossing coordinate will be close to the final x_cross value.

Trail consolidation. From roughly tick 500 onward, watch the broad chemo field begin to narrow into distinct trails. The first trails to emerge are those most heavily reinforced — typically the path that established first contact with the food. Competing paths fade gradually.

x_cross stability. Watch the x-cross-history plot carefully after first contact is established. Ask: does x_cross settle immediately, or does it drift over the subsequent pruning phase? This is the mechanistic discriminator between Huygens and  flux-optimization.

Zone boundary behavior. Watch what happens to agents as they cross y = 0. In Condition A (Zone 1 fast), agents that cross into Zone 2 immediately slow down — their effective step size halves. This creates a visible density increase just inside the Zone 2 boundary as agents compress. This is the direct physical analog of light slowing at an optical interface.

## THINGS TO TRY

Test the Snell's Law prediction quantitatively.

Before running Condition A, calculate the expected x_cross from the formula: sin(θ₁)/sin(θ₂) = V1/V2, where θ₁ is the incidence angle from the source to a crossing point on the boundary, and θ₂ is the angle from the boundary to the food. With V1/V2 = 2.0 and the default source and food positions, the predicted x_cross is approximately +40.
Run 10 replicates and compare the mean to your prediction.

Test the symmetry prediction.

Run Condition A and record the mean x_cross. Switch to Condition B (swapped zones) and run the same number of replicates. Snell's Law predicts that x_cross(B) ≈ −x_cross(A). Any asymmetry indicates a confound from the source or food placement geometry.

Vary the speed ratio.

Set V1/V2 to 1.5, 2.0, and 3.0 in turn (adjusting V2 while keeping V1 = 1.0). Snell's Law predicts x_cross should increase monotonically with the speed ratio. Plot mean x_cross against the predicted value for each ratio to test whether the simulation tracks the prediction.

Run the null model.

Set Condition C (homogeneous: V1 = V2 = 1.0). The expected x_cross is approximately 0 — the straight-line path from lower-left to upper-right crosses the boundary at the center. Any systematic deviation from zero identifies lattice anisotropy or geometric bias that must be subtracted from Conditions A and B. Watch the pruning phase in slow motion.

After the first connection to the food is established, reduce the simulation speed using the NetLogo speed slider and watch the x-cross monitor tick by tick. Can you see the crossing point shift as competing paths are pruned? Does the final dominant tube arrive at a sharper angle than the first exploratory connection?

Test sensitivity to DECAY-RATE.

Run 10 replicates at DECAY-RATE = 0.02, 0.05, and 0.10 with all other parameters fixed. Higher decay should produce a faster, cleaner pruning but may eliminate some valid paths prematurely. Does x_cross change systematically with decay rate? It should not if the model is correctly encoding traversal time and not selection bias.

## EXTENDING THE MODEL

Boundary transient (gradual speed change).

The current model switches agent speed instantaneously at y = 0. Real Physarum may respond gradually to a medium change as it physically encounters new substrate conditions. Add a transition zone of width W patches centered on y = 0, in which medium-speed interpolates linearly from V1 to V2. Test whether the transition width affects x_cross or only the sharpness of the angle change.

Obstacle avoidance.

Add impassable patches to the world (dark regions agents cannot enter). Physarum is known to navigate around obstacles while maintaining network connectivity. Does the refraction prediction still hold when a small obstacle is placed near the expected crossing point?

Multiple food sources.

Add a second food source at a different location. Physarum is known to build Steiner-tree-like networks connecting multiple nutrient nodes. Does the zone boundary produce refraction in each branch of the multi-source network independently?

Oscillatory dynamics.

Real Physarum exploration is rhythmically pulsed — the pseudopodial fan advances and retracts with a period of approximately 1–2 minutes. Implement an oscillatory modulation of DEPOSIT-AMOUNT (varying sinusoidally with a fixed period) and test whether this affects path geometry or only slows consolidation.

Nutrient gradient within zones.

Add a chemoattractant field that decreases with distance from the food source, independent of the turtle-deposited trail. This models diffusing nutrients from the food. Does the resulting gradient interact with the zone speed differential to shift x_cross?

Obstacle as a third medium.

Instead of impassable patches, create a third zone with a distinct medium-speed, modeling a substrate stripe of different viscosity crossing the world diagonally. Does the path exhibit a second refraction event at the second boundary, consistent with a layered optical medium?

## NETLOGO FEATURES

Patch-level speed multiplier. Agent speed is read from the patch property medium-speed at each tick rather than being a global or turtle variable. This means a single slider change to V1 or V2 during setup propagates correctly to all agents without requiring any turtle-level bookkeeping.

diffuse primitive. NetLogo's built-in diffuse primitive spreads a patch variable to all 8 Moore neighbors simultaneously in a single command. This is computationally efficient but note that the diffusion rate interacts with the decay step: the effective diffusion is approximately DIFFUSION-RATE per tick, but the post-diffusion chemo value on each patch also absorbs diffused-in amounts from neighbors. Test the primitive in isolation with a single point source to verify the spreading behavior matches your biological expectations before integrating it into the full model.

patch-at-heading-and-distance for sensor sampling. The three-sensor chemo sampling uses patch-at-heading-and-distance to read chemo at locations the turtle has not yet moved to. This is the standard Jones (2010) approach and avoids the need to spawn temporary agents or use complex trigonometry. Note that this primitive returns nobody for positions outside world bounds — the chemo-at reporter handles this by returning 0, which causes boundary agents to turn away from walls naturally.

file-open / file-print for CSV export. Results are written to CSV using NetLogo's file I/O primitives inside the export-results procedure. Note that file-open in append mode will add to an existing file across runs — useful for batch experiments but requires manually deleting output files before a new experiment series. Consider adding a setup check that warns if the output files already exist.

BehaviorSpace for batch runs. The 50-replicate experiment design is best executed using NetLogo's built-in BehaviorSpace tool rather than manually clicking SETUP/GO repeatedly. BehaviorSpace can vary the random seed across runs, collect output variables at run termination, and export to a spreadsheet automatically. The time-course output (x_cross logged every tick) requires a reporter that returns the full list — consult the BehaviorSpace documentation for how to export list variables.

## RELATED MODELS

Slime Mold Network (NetLogo Models Library, CCL Northwestern)
URL: https://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/models/SlimeMoldNetwork

A graph-based NetLogo model of Physarum network formation using food nodes and connection reinforcement. Uses a different architecture (graph rather than spatial agents) but reproduces similar emergent network topologies. Useful as a reference for NetLogo code style.

Ants (NetLogo Models Library)
URL: https://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/models/Ants

The canonical NetLogo chemoattractant-trail model. Turtles deposit pheromone, diffusion and decay maintain the field, and positive feedback produces foraging trails. The Physarum agent mechanism in this model is architecturally similar — the key difference is the three-sensor gradient-climbing rule replacing the probabilistic turning of the Ants model.

Slime Mold (NetLogo Models Library)
URL: https://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/models/SlimeMold

Models aggregation behavior in Dictyostelium discoideum (a cellular slime mold, distinct from Physarum). Different organism and mechanism but illustrates chemoattractant signaling in a NetLogo context.

Jones (2010) Virtual Physarum

The direct computational basis for this model. Jeff Jones's agent model uses sensory particles on a 2D grid with a chemo deposit-diffuse- decay cycle. The sensor geometry (SD = 9, SA = 45°) used in this model is taken directly from Jones's published parameter set.

Reference: Jones, J.A. (2010). Characteristics of Pattern Formation and Evolution in Approximations of Physarum Transport Networks. Artificial Life 16(2), 127–153.

## CREDITS AND REFERENCES

Model designed by:
John Peach, eurAIka sciences, 2026.
Science council methodology: eurAIka Science Council
(Claude, Perplexity, ChatGPT, Gemini), Rounds 1–2, 2026-05-02.

Primary biological reference: Nakagaki, T., Yamada, H., & Tóth, Á. (2000). Maze-solving by an amoeboid organism. Nature, 407, 470. The foundational experimental demonstration of Physarum path optimization.

Primary agent model reference:
Jones, J.A. (2010). Characteristics of Pattern Formation and Evolution in Approximations of Physarum Transport Networks. Artificial Life, 16(2), 127–153.
The sensor-particle architecture this model is based on.

Flux-reinforcement dynamics reference:
Tero, A., Kobayashi, R., & Nakagaki, T. (2007). A mathematical model for adaptive transport network in path finding by true slime mold. Journal of Theoretical Biology, 244(4), 553–564.

The governing equation for tube conductance dynamics:
dD_ij/dt = f(|Q_ij|) − γ D_ij.

Network optimization reference:
Tero, A., et al. (2010). Rules for Biologically Inspired Adaptive Network Design. Science, 327(5964), 439–442.
Physarum network formation applied to transport network design; demonstrates least-energy-dissipation as the governing optimization principle.

Variational / least-action framework:
Facchini, A., et al. (2025). A Lagrangian framework for Physarum network organization. arXiv:2511.08531.
Formalizes Physarum network optimization as a variational problem minimizing global energy dissipation — the theoretical context for distinguishing least-time from least-energy predictions.

Physarum growth rate data:
Community lab practice note on temperature-dependent doubling time.
slimoco.ning.com/forum/topics/effect-of-temperature-on-slime-mould-growth
Source for the working estimate v₁/v₂ ≈ 2 (25°C vs 15°C).
Not peer-reviewed; treat as an order-of-magnitude prior.]]></info>
